    "body": "# The Shifting Economics of MVP Funding\n**TL;DR:** Some observers suggest that the traditional VC advantage in funding minimum viable products may be eroding as the cost to build early-stage prototypes has reportedly dropped significantly.\n## A Conversation Worth Following\n\nA recent observation making the rounds in startup circles suggests that venture capitalists may be navigating unfamiliar territory when it comes to their traditional role in funding minimum viable products.\n\nThe argument, as one commentator put it, is that the VC \"edge\" in funding MVPs has diminished as founders can reportedly bootstrap early prototypes for relatively modest sums—some claim as low as a few hundred dollars, depending on the product.\n\n### Context Matters\n\nIt's worth noting that MVP costs vary enormously by sector, complexity, and founder capabilities. What holds true for a simple software tool may not apply to hardware, regulated industries, or products requiring significant infrastructure.\n\nThat said, the broader conversation touches on a legitimate question: as no-code tools, AI assistants, and cloud infrastructure continue to reduce early development costs, where does the value proposition for early-stage investors shift?\n\nWe'll be watching how this dynamic evolves—and whether it changes the calculus for both founders and funders at the earliest stages.",
